 <p>A Georgia man agreed to plead guilty to federal racketeering charges associated with the so-called Carder.su criminal enterprise that trafficked and manufactured stolen and counterfeit credit cards resulting in $50 million in losses globally.</p>
<p>The defendant, Cameron Harrison (also known as "Kilobit"), was not offered a plea deal but faces years behind bars when sentenced later this year in a Las Vegas federal court, according to court records unveiled Wednesday.</p>
<p>As many as 55 members of the Carder.su group have been charged in the <a href="http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/22-year-old-guilty-racketeering-online-identity-theft-scheme">nation's first case in which old-school racketeering laws</a> were invoked against a cybercrime group. Eight others have pleaded guilty. Trial awaits some of them and many remain at large.</p>
