<a href="http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/fire-tv.jpg"><img src="http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/fire-tv-640x426.jpg" srcset="http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/fire-tv-1280x853.jpg 2x"></a><div class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em">
<div class="caption-text"><a href="http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/fire-tv.jpg" class="caption-link" rel="nofollow">From left, the Fire TV box, the remote, and the power cable that come in the box. </a></div> </div>
</div>
<h2 id="onthehardwareandsetup">On the hardware and setup</h2>
<p>Our review unit came with a separate HDMI cable in the bag, which means you'll have to supply your own. Everything else, including batteries for the remote, comes in the box. The Fire TV itself is simple, flat, and black without even a set of feet to hold it up off the ground. Instead, the bottom is surfaced with a rubbery plastic.</p>
